                        Populations General Description
                      ===================================


Introduction:
------------

Populations are a means for keeping track of groups of objects,
usually NPCs, and refreshing the population via a generic 
generation facility. With a population, you can have a group of
wandering monsters in your area keep its numbers up without
having to make them all unique objects.



Concepts
--------

A population is a group of objects, and is held by a POPULATION
object as defined in <mudlib.h>. The population has a key that
should be unique on the mud, a set of filenames to clone when
the population needs refreshing, a set of generators for creating
the clones when necessary, and a number of parameters governing
refresh time and so forth.

The population should be created by a single room or object that
will persist. That object doesn't need to keep track of the 
population; it just needs to create it. The POPULATION_D is 
tasked with tracking population objects.

A generator is an object that places a newly created member of
the population somewhere, like in a room or other object. There
is a generic generator (ROOM_GENERATOR) that places new objects
in a particular room and prints a message to everyone in the 
room.

Files creating and configuring population objects should include
<population.h>.

Basic Functionality
-------------------

POPULATION:
void set_key_name(string name)
- Set the name that the population daemon will use to track 
  the population.

string query_key_name()
- Queries the name.

void add_object_file(string filename)
- Adds an object file to the list of files that can be cloned
  when refreshing the population. A population can be configured
  to pick one object file randomly when refreshing, or sequence
  through the object files one by one.

void remove_object_file(string filename)
- Removes the filename from the object file list.

void add_generator(object generator)
- Adds a generator to the list of generators to use when 
  refreshing the population. A population can be configured
  to pick one generator randomly when refreshing, or sequence
  through the generators one by one.

void remove_generator(object generator)
- Removes the generator from the generator list.

void set_clone_type(int type)
- POP_CLONE_RANDOM or POP_CLONE_SEQ. RANDOM will choose one
  of the object files randomly when it needs to clone an
  object. SEQ will sequence through the object files in
  order, and start over at the beginning, as objects are
  cloned.

void set_generate_type(int type)
- GEN_CHOOSE_RANDOM or GEN_CHOOSE_SEQ. RANDOM will choose one
  of the generators randomly when it needs to generate an
  object. SEQ will sequence through the generators in order,
  and start over at the beginning, as objects are cloned.

void set_auto_check(int auto)
- If auto check is on, the population object will check its
  list of objects that it has created, determining if the
  object has been destructed or not. Without auto check,
  the objects must alert the population object manually
  with remove_population_object.

void set_min_number(int min)
- Set the minimum number of objects that should be in 
  the population. When the number falls below the minimum,
  the population will use the generators to create new
  population members.

void set_update_interval(int secs)
- Sets how long between checks for population refreshes.

int query_update_interval()
- Query how long between checks for population refreshes.

int query_generate_seq()
- Queries the index of the last generation sequence. Only
  useful if GEN_CHOOSE_SEQ was used.

int query_clone_seq()
- Queries the index of the last cloning sequence. Only
  useful if POP_CLONE_SEQ was used.

void add_population_object(object obj)
- Add an object to the population for tracking. Necessary
  only if you wish to add objects manually.

void remove_population_object(object obj)
- Remove an object from the population. Necessary only if
  you are not using auto check.

object *query_object_clones()
- Returns a list of the current objects in the population.

Generators:
Basically, any object that has a "void generate(object obj)"
function can be a generator. It should take the object and
do whatever is necessary to enter the object into the game,
like place it in a room or something similar. The generator
can also perform additional setup of the generated object,
if desired.

There is a generic room generator (ROOM_GENERATOR) that
will place generated objects in a given room, and print
a defined message to all occupants of the room. It has
the following interface:

void set_room(string filename)
- Sets the filename of the room where the objects will be
  placed.

void set_room_message(string msg)
- Sets the message that will be printed to the room when
  the newly generated object is moved there.

Population daemon:
The population daemon (POPULATION_D) tracks all of the
populations on the mud. If a population is added of the
same key as an existing population, the current population
members will be moved to the new population, and the old
population object will be destructed.

If the population daemon is updated, all current populations
will be destructed and lost.

void add_population(object pop)
- Adds the population to the tracking system, and calls
  startup() on it to initiate the refreshing call_out.

void remove_population(string key)
- Removes the population of that key and destructs it.


Example
-------
The following code will create a population that randomly 
selects between two types of baby demons when a population
of baby demons falls below 12. The refresh check is made
every 2 minutes. The two rooms, forest6 and forest8, will
be selected between in order when a new baby demon is
created.

  object pop, gen;
  string str;

  pop = clone_object(POPULATION);
  pop->set_key_name("malraux.newbie.demon");
  pop->set_clone_type(POP_CLONE_RANDOM);
  pop->set_generate_type(GEN_CHOOSE_SEQ);
  pop->set_auto_check(1);
  pop->set_min_number(12);
  pop->add_object_file(MALNEWBIE + "obj/babydemon1");
  pop->add_object_file(MALNEWBIE + "obj/babydemon2");
  pop->set_update_interval(120);

  str = "\
The obscene flesh quivers suddenly. A quivering slit opens in the side\n\
of the mound, showing a purplish interior. A small figure is pushed out,\n\
and a new demon is born.\n";

  gen = clone_object(ROOM_GENERATOR);
  gen->set_room(MALNEWBIE + "forest6");
  gen->set_room_message(str);
  pop->add_generator(gen);

  gen = clone_object(ROOM_GENERATOR);
  gen->set_room(MALNEWBIE + "forest8");
  gen->set_room_message(str);
  pop->add_generator(gen);

  POPULATION_D->add_population(pop);


